      <span class="label">Colophon</span>
      <h1 class="article__title">Read everything. Keep almost nothing.</h1>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There is too much to read, and most of it isn’t worth the time. Lede exists to fix the ratio. It watches the places technology and AI actually break first — over a thousand of them, from the labs and the front pages to the long tail of practitioner blogs — and surfaces the handful of things that matter, with a clear account of <em>why</em>.</p>

      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <p>Every cycle, Lede pulls from <strong>1,103 sources</strong>: aggregators, research feeds, company and lab blogs, newsletters, and the deep bench of individual engineers who quietly write the best things on the internet. Stories that surface across many independent sources rise; the rest settle.</p>
      <p>The shortlist gets read — actually read — by a language model briefed to be a ruthless editor: it scores relevance, pulls the load-bearing details, and writes the one line that tells you whether to care. Marketing dressed as news, thin rewrites, and benchmark theater get cut. What remains is ranked and explained.</p>
      <p>Once a week, the best of it is distilled into a single digest: organized by what’s actually happening, links to primary sources, and a flat refusal to launder any company’s framing as fact.</p>

      <h2>Principles</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Primary sources first.</strong> The paper, the repo, the filing — not the press release about them. When something’s paywalled, the best free read is found and linked.</li>
        <li><strong>Why, not just what.</strong> Anyone can list links. Each pick says what it means and who should care.</li>
        <li><strong>Unbiased by construction.</strong> Claims are attributed as claims. Disagreement is shown, not smoothed over.</li>
        <li><strong>No inbox required.</strong> Lede lives in your feed reader. Subscribe to everything, or just the channels you want.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Subscribe</h2>
      <p>Point any RSS reader at <a href="/rss.xml">the full feed</a>, or pick a channel from the front page. New picks arrive as they’re curated; the digest, once a week.</p>
